SIMPLE: agglutinate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Agglutinate
<hw>Ag*glu"ti*nate</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Agglutinated</conjf>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Agglutinating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>agglutinatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>agglutinare</ets> to glue or
cement to a thing; <ets>ad</ets> + <ets>glutinare</ets> to glue;
<ets>gluten</ets> glue. See <er>Glue</er>.]</ety> <def>To unite, or
cause to adhere, as with glue or other viscous substance; to unite by
causing an adhesion of substances.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Agglutinate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Agglutinate
<hw>Ag*glu"ti*nate</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>United with glue or as with glue; cemented together.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>Consisting of root words
combined but not materially altered as to form or meaning; <as>as,
<ex>agglutinate</ex> forms, languages, etc.</as> See
<er>Agglutination</er>, 2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Agglutination</ent>⟦br⟧
